fferences in this context. The authors posit that it is necessary to dissolve the question of universalism versus relativism by replacing the ideal language paradigm with a paradigm of family resemblances and that it is not necessary to share a common language to engage in comparison. Numerous case studies are presented, including many comparisons of Western and Chinese concepts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPhilosophy, Comparative. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aLiterature : Translation. 4aPhilosophy : Comparative Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Comparative Religion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Methodology.2bisacsh1 avan Brakel, Jaap, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846017840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438460178423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438460178/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles